item.description:
Problem Statement If \(p\) is the perimeter of a right triangle with side lengths \({a,b,c}\), then there are exactly 3 solutions for \(p = 120\):
\begin{equation*} {20,48,52}, {24,45,51}, {30,40,50} \end{equation*}
For which value of \(p \le N\) is the number of solutions maximized? If there are multiple possible answers, print the minimum one.
My Algorithm A famous method of generating Pythagorean triples is due to Euclid:
\begin{equation} a = m^2 - n^2 \quad b = 2mn \quad c = m^2 + n^2 \quad m &gt; n \label{generating} \end{equation}
